# SORTING ALGORITHMS PERFORMANCE ANALYSIS

## 1. Aim of Experiment

To implement and analyze the performance of Insertion Sort, Merge Sort, and Quick Sort using different types of datasets and compare their execution times with theoretical time complexities.

---

## 2. Introduction

Sorting is the process of arranging data in a particular order such as ascending or descending. Sorting algorithms are important in computer science because they improve searching and data processing efficiency.

In this experiment, three sorting algorithms were implemented:

- Insertion Sort
- Merge Sort
- Quick Sort

The algorithms were tested on:
- Random datasets
- Sorted datasets
- Reverse sorted datasets

Dataset sizes used:
- 1000 elements
- 5000 elements
- 10000 elements

---

## 3. Algorithms Used

### 3.1 Insertion Sort

Insertion Sort works by taking one element at a time and inserting it into its correct position in the sorted part of the array.

Time Complexity:
- Best Case: O(n)
- Average Case: O(n²)
- Worst Case: O(n²)

Properties:
- Stable: Yes
- In-place: Yes

---

### 3.2 Merge Sort

Merge Sort divides the array into smaller parts, sorts them recursively, and merges them back together.

Time Complexity:
- Best Case: O(n log n)
- Average Case: O(n log n)
- Worst Case: O(n log n)

Properties:
- Stable: Yes
- In-place: No

---

### 3.3 Quick Sort

Quick Sort selects a pivot element and partitions the array into smaller and larger elements around the pivot.

Time Complexity:
- Best Case: O(n log n)
- Average Case: O(n log n)
- Worst Case: O(n²)

Properties:
- Stable: No
- In-place: Yes

---

## 4. Dataset Generation

Three types of datasets were generated:

1. Random Data
   Elements arranged randomly.

2. Sorted Data
   Elements already sorted in ascending order.

3. Reverse Sorted Data
   Elements sorted in descending order.

Dataset sizes:
- 1000
- 5000
- 10000

---

## 5. Experimental Results

The execution times of each sorting algorithm were measured using Python’s time module.

Sample Output:

Dataset Size: 1000

Random Data
Insertion Sort: 0.032145 seconds
Merge Sort: 0.002341 seconds
Quick Sort: 0.001954 seconds

(Add your complete output.txt results here.)

---

## 6. Observation and Analysis

- Insertion Sort performed well for small datasets but became slower for large datasets due to its O(n²) complexity.
- Merge Sort showed consistent performance for all dataset types because its complexity remains O(n log n).
- Quick Sort was generally the fastest algorithm for random datasets.
- Quick Sort performance may decrease in the worst case when pivot selection is poor.

---

## 7. Quick Sort Worst Case Analysis

The worst case of Quick Sort occurs when the pivot divides the array unevenly, such as:
- Already sorted arrays
- Reverse sorted arrays

In this situation, the time complexity becomes O(n²).

This makes Quick Sort slower compared to Merge Sort in worst-case scenarios.

---

## 8. Stability and In-place Nature

| Algorithm       | Stable | In-place |
|----------------|---------|----------|
| Insertion Sort | Yes     | Yes      |
| Merge Sort     | Yes     | No       |
| Quick Sort     | No      | Yes      |

---

## 9. Conclusion

In this experiment, three sorting algorithms were implemented and analyzed successfully.

- Insertion Sort is simple but inefficient for large datasets.
- Merge Sort provides stable and reliable performance.
- Quick Sort is generally the fastest but can perform poorly in the worst case.

The experimental results closely matched the theoretical time complexities of the algorithms.